12. Assignment

The Parties declare that the License is concluded intuitu personae. Consequently, neither Party is authorized to assign or transfer, in whole or in part, whether for a fee or free of charge, the rights and obligations pertaining to the License, without the prior written agreement of the other Party.

13. Termination and Expiration of the Agreement

The Owner may, if the USER fails to perform their obligations, terminate the License. In this case, the Owner shall inform the USER of its intention to terminate the License by sending a registered letter with acknowledgment of receipt in which the nature of the breach will be indicated.

Termination shall take effect either immediately when the breach cannot be remedied, or, otherwise, within a period of thirty (30) days from the receipt of this letter if the USER has not remedied their breach to the Owner's satisfaction during this period.

The expiration of the License occurs either at its normal term or after its termination by one of the Parties.

This expiration, regardless of the cause, shall not affect the clauses relating to confidentiality, publications, and intellectual property.

Upon expiration of the License for any cause whatsoever, the USER undertakes to cease using the Program. They undertake to destroy the license files and all original media and copies of the Program, even partial, in their possession, including any backup copies, within a maximum period of one (1) month.

The USER shall establish, sign, and transmit to the correspondent mentioned in Article 11, a certificate attesting to the destruction of the Program and any copies in their possession.

14. Force Majeure

Neither Party shall be liable for the total or partial non-performance of its obligations caused by an event constituting force majeure within the meaning of Article 1218 of the French Civil Code and recognized as such by the jurisprudence of French courts and tribunals.

The Party invoking an event constituting force majeure must notify the other Party within thirty (30) days following the occurrence of this event. Furthermore, it undertakes to deploy its best efforts to limit the consequences of this event.

The performance deadlines shall be extended for a period determined by mutual agreement between the Parties.

In the event that a force majeure event persists for more than thirty (30) days from the date on which the force majeure event was notified to the other Party, the Parties shall meet to determine the conditions under which the License will be maintained or terminated.

15. Severability (Nullity)

If one or more provisions of the License are held to be invalid or declared as such pursuant to a law, a regulation, or following a final decision rendered by a competent jurisdiction, the other provisions of the License shall retain their full force and scope.

16. Headings

